Oh, did line 65 erase the result of making `EVALB`?  🤦‍♂️   Sorry...

The only issue with doing it this way is that we won't have all of the scripts.  That's probably not an issue...?  I guess this seems fine for now, and if someone wants a particular script in the docker image that's not present, they can add it later.

@murphp15, the previous line copied an entire directory.  Turns out that caused some problems, because of the earlier lines.  Most anticipated uses of the docker container don't actually need all of the scripts in the directory, so to avoid clobbering the stuff built on line 57, we can just copy over a few scripts that we need instead of the whole thing.

I'd rather do something like that: 
```python
                peername = request.remote
                if peername is not None:
                    kwargs = {}
                    if isinstance(peername, ipaddress.IPv4Address):
                        kwargs['ipv4'] = str(peername)
                    elif isinstance(peername, ipaddress.IPv6Address):
                        kwargs['ipv6'] = str(peername)
                    else:
                        try:
                            peer_ip = ipaddress.ip_address(peername)
                        except (ipaddress.AddressValueError, ValueError):
                            pass  # if we're okay with swallowing the Exception
                        if isinstance(peer_ip, ipaddress.IPv4Address):
                            kwargs['ipv4'] = str(peer_ip)
                        elif isinstance(peer_ip, ipaddress.IPv6Address):
                            kwargs['ipv6'] = str(peer_ip)
                    if kwargs:
                        span.remote_endpoint(None, **kwargs)
```
Done under the assumption `remote_endpoint` expects `str`.
It has the benefit of using `ipaddress`'s formatting/checker.

A better version would be to always transform into a `IPv4Address`/`IPv6Address` and handle them directly. Strings are not good anyway.

But I don't know enough of this project anyway so I may be wrong about that last part.

That won't be possible since the related resource has ReadOnlyAuthorization. If you want ConstantResource to have ReadOnlyAuthorization, but for EquationResource.constancts to be changeable, you'll need to create another resource with a different Authorization that permits creating/updating.

    class ConstantResource(ModelResource):
        class Meta:
            always_return_data = True
            queryset = Constant.objects.all()
            authenticaion = Authentication()
            authorization = ReadOnlyAuthorization()


    class WritableConstantResource(ConstantResource):
        class Meta(ConstantResource.Meta):
            authorization = AMorePermissibleAuthorization()


    class EquationResource(ModelResource):
        description = fields.CharField()
        constants = fields.ToManyField(
            WritableConstantResource, 'constants', related_name='equations', null=True,
            blank=True, full=True)

